		<table width="100%">
		<tr>
			<td>
				<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="3"><b>    Lowlevel Guide to Unrest</b></font>
					<br>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">
					<b><A href="mailto:veygoth@stax.net">Xangis</a> | 
		            12/26/1999 12:13:36 PM</b></font></p>
		         <a href="guides.asp">
		         <font face="verdana" size="2">Return to guide listing.</font></a>
					
					<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">Lowlevel Guide to Unrest<BR>
<BR>
Unrest can be a very nasty place for both first-time visitors and experienced veterans. Why is that? Because undead just never know when to give up. This guide should help you out as a new visitor and probably be useful at least as long as yard trash gives you experience. I&#8217;m also hoping that someone will write a midlevel/highlevel guide to Unrest.<BR>
<BR>
Upon a traveller&#8217;s first visit to unrest, they should be somewhere between level 13 and 16. Anything less is just silly. When you first arrive, you&#8217;re likely to get pummeled and slaughtered by all the rampant trains of destruction-spouting walking dead, die multiple times, and probably leave never to return again.<BR>
<BR>
However, the Estate of Unrest is a great dungeon if you know your way around. Much of this guide is common sense stuff that will apply no matter what the zone.<BR>
<BR>
Learn the Maze<BR>
<BR>
The maze is actually a very small maze but once you know the 3 spawn points for creatures you can pick a great spot to rest and/or meditate. You can also use these 3 spawn points to fight creatures one-on-one without fear of getting run over by a train. If you&#8217;re soloing, this is a great place to be, because by the time you&#8217;ve killed all 3 of the creatures in the maze and recovered/healed/meditated, they&#8217;ve started to respawn and you can start all over again. Very rarely do creatures wander into the maze, and often when they do it&#8217;s so ugly outside the maze that you&#8217;re still safer inside. It&#8217;s also possible to avoid a PK by darting into the maze and running around it enough to get him off your trail.<BR>
<BR>
The Courtyard is Scary<BR>
<BR>
You should only fight in the courtyard if you have a deathwish or can kill trains easily. Most of the trains that come through Unrest run along the left wall or down the center path, and if you&#8217;re standing in the courtyard when one runs by you will almost always get very wrinkled.<BR>
<BR>
Fight at the Zone<BR>
<BR>
If you&#8217;re going up against something that you don&#8217;t know whether you&#8217;ll be able to handle comfortably, run to the zone and fight there. If you get into trouble or if too much follows you there, safety is just a step away.<BR>
<BR>
Hang out at the Waterfall<BR>
<BR>
I&#8217;m not sure what else to call it, it&#8217;s in the back corner behind the house. There is a small patch of land behind the house surrounded by a small moat and with a little stream running down a small hill into the moat. There are usually 1-2 things on the patch of land, and this is generally a pretty safe place to fight because it&#8217;s totally out of the path of any trains. You can usually safely meditate/rest at the top of the hill, though a respawn might notice you and cause a little trouble. This is rare and you won&#8217;t usually have to worry about it. There is one point where you can jump across the moat without touching the water, and this is right next to the gazebo. Practice this jump because sometimes the tormented dead fall in the water, and you could get jumped by 1-3 of them when you get into the water.<BR>
<BR>
Beware of Beetles<BR>
<BR>
This is a lesson you will learn very quickly. The death beetles assist undead in unrest, and a close battle against a tormented dead can quite easily end up you dying to a tormented dead and five death beetles. Try to fight where the death beetles are very scarce and/or won&#8217;t see you. It&#8217;s not a bad idea to kill all of the nearby beetles before deciding to pull anything from the house if you are low enough level that the beetles can cause you any serious problems in a rough fight (under 20). You&#8217;ll learn to hate them, but eventually you&#8217;ll get enough levels that they&#8217;ll start to leave you alone.<BR>
<BR>
Trains<BR>
<BR>
Trains here are ugly, instead of panicking and running to the zone when someone shouts train, you&#8217;re best off just getting quite far out of the way where you won&#8217;t be noticed. If someone trains some of the higher level creatures, running through the tunnel after them is a guaranteed death sentence. Be sure to announce if you or any of your party has just started a train. Some people don&#8217;t realize that trains are a constant phenomenon in Unrest and aren&#8217;t always expecting them.<BR>
<BR>
Groups<BR>
<BR>
Unrest is an excellent place to group because many clerics are drawn to the place because of the powers they have over undead. Finding a healer for a group is usually pretty easy, and I can recall groups I&#8217;ve been in that have been all healers. The most important thing is that the group have a skilled puller who knows when what and where to pull, and when to run the stuff to zone rather than to the group. Be coordinated and make sure you know what everyone is doing or will be doing in combat. Use crowd control tactics if you can, and always work together, because you never know what&#8217;s going to land on top of you.<BR>
<BR>
Pullers<BR>
<BR>
It can be an eternal debate who makes a good puller and who makes a bad puller, but the main thing is that the person has to know the zone very well and know how to bring what you can handle. If you get a good group together and nobody knows how to pull, you might as well all disband and hunt solo, because you will die and lose more exp that you will gain in a group. Here are my opinions on the following puller types:<BR>
<BR>
HEALER:<BR>
<BR>
Clerics, Shamans, and Druids &#8211; Healers can pull, yes, but while pulling they can&#8217;t do a very good job of healing, and pulling usually precludes meditating. If you&#8217;ve got invisibility to undead, that&#8217;s certainly nice to have, but healers should generally not pull unless they can help it.<BR>
<BR>
MAGES:<BR>
<BR>
Wizards, Enchanters, and the like are very good at making creatures angry, but pulling with a mage is a bad idea, especially in this place.<BR>
<BR>
MONKS:<BR>
<BR>
Monks make great pullers in Unrest. If a monk gets into trouble and/or pulls too much, he can just fall over dead. The residents will think he&#8217;s converted over to their side and the undead bartender will probably even give him a free drink.<BR>
<BR>
MELEE CLASSES:<BR>
<BR>
Natural pullers, but always be sure to get a buff or three, especially Spirit of Wolf. Warriors don&#8217;t need to concentrate like the casters do, so being beat about doesen&#8217;t really cause any problems.<BR>
<BR>
Be Very Afraid<BR>
<BR>
There are some things to be very afraid of as a lowlevel in Unrest. Festering Hags. Tentacle Terrors. Werebats, and a bunch of other stuff. All of these can wrinkle you to oblivion quicker than you know it. If you see or hear something you know can kill you, get out of the way quick. Most things that you haven&#8217;t heard of can probably easily kill you, so just avoid them.<BR>
<BR>
Keep Your Eyes Open<BR>
<BR>
Often you will suffer from the mistakes of others. Try not to fight next to a group that obviously can&#8217;t handle all that it pulls or doesen&#8217;t know what it&#8217;s doing. A bad pull doesen&#8217;t necessarily only kill the group that pulled it. However, if you camp out next to a skilled or higher level group that does know what they&#8217;re doing, they can save your butt by taking out your extras if need be. Find a place you like to hunt, and just keep an eye on what everyone else is doing.<BR>
<BR>

			<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
					</p>
			</td>
